01:34:20,661 --> 01:34:22,541
I'm taking these with me.

1717
01:34:22,788 --> 01:34:24,118
I'm taking all of these with me.

1718
01:34:24,164 --> 01:34:26,584
I want all of these boxed up,
and I'm taking them.

1719
01:34:26,625 --> 01:34:27,885
You're trespassing!

1720
01:34:27,918 --> 01:34:29,168
It's not your patent!

1721
01:34:29,586 --> 01:34:31,496
These are my designs!

1722
01:34:32,840 --> 01:34:35,180
I'm not going anywhere without my molds.

1723
01:34:36,093 --> 01:34:37,803
What? No. No.

1724
01:34:37,845 --> 01:34:40,265
This is not stealing,
this is my property!

1725
01:34:40,305 --> 01:34:41,555
This is my property.

1726
01:34:41,598 --> 01:34:45,058
I have all of these designs.
These are all mine. They belong to me!

1727
01:34:45,102 --> 01:34:48,862
She's from out of state, John!
You've known me 15 years!

1728
01:34:48,897 --> 01:34:50,647
All right, come on, ma'am.
You're trespassing.

1729
01:34:50,691 --> 01:34:52,401
- What?
- Yeah. Come on.

1730
01:34:52,442 --> 01:34:53,942
- I'm not trespassing.
- Yeah, you're trespassing.

1731
01:34:53,986 --> 01:34:55,106
I was in his office.

1732
01:34:55,153 --> 01:34:56,653
- You don't know. Come on.
- He let me into his...

1733
01:34:56,697 --> 01:34:58,197
Gerhardt, you're not gonna
get away with this.

1734
01:34:58,240 --> 01:34:59,780
- You're not gonna get away with this!
- Be careful what you're saying.

1735
01:34:59,825 --> 01:35:01,875
- You're a thief! You're a thief, Gerhardt!
- Be careful, come on, come on.

1736
01:35:01,910 --> 01:35:03,240
Be careful. Come on, stop it.

1737
01:35:03,287 --> 01:35:05,497
- This is stealing!
- Hey, hey, stop it. Come on.

1738
01:35:05,539 --> 01:35:06,539
All right.

1739
01:35:09,626 --> 01:35:11,586
Watch your step. All right.

1740
01:35:19,636 --> 01:35:21,006
What about Trudy's money, Joy?

1741
01:35:21,054 --> 01:35:23,184
You have to pay back Trudy's money.

1742
01:35:23,223 --> 01:35:24,893
This is only getting worse.

1743
01:35:24,933 --> 01:35:26,813
I predicted tragedy, Joy.

1744
01:35:27,269 --> 01:35:29,309
You're racking up quite a steep bill.

1745
01:35:29,354 --> 01:35:32,614
We had to fly out here, bail you out.

1746
01:35:32,649 --> 01:35:35,779
Plus it cost us an extra $10,000
for Ray Cagney...

1747
01:35:35,819 --> 01:35:38,319
this California patent attorney,
to get us to this point.

1748
01:35:38,363 --> 01:35:40,993
We got the state to decline prosecution.

1749
01:35:41,033 --> 01:35:43,243
They see it's a contract dispute.

1750
01:35:43,285 --> 01:35:46,915
When you paid royalties
to Derek Markham in Texas...

1751
01:35:46,955 --> 01:35:50,995
it put all your parts and molds
under the umbrella of their patent.

1752
01:35:51,919 --> 01:35:55,169
I see you brought your drawings
and hung them to prove your design.

1753
01:35:55,214 --> 01:35:57,844
But it's impossible to fight it now.

1754
01:35:57,883 --> 01:36:00,343
You were not properly advised.

1755
01:36:01,678 --> 01:36:03,178
Cristy, please!

1756
01:36:03,222 --> 01:36:04,352
Tony, take her to bed.

1757
01:36:04,389 --> 01:36:06,639
I don't wanna go to bed.
I wanna stay here.

1758
01:36:06,683 --> 01:36:08,183
I paid those royalties...

1759
01:36:08,227 --> 01:36:09,347
because you told me to.

1760
01:36:09,394 --> 01:36:12,234
Because your lawyer told me to.

1761
01:36:12,272 --> 01:36:16,152
Our lawyer was mistaken.
This happens sometimes in business.

1762
01:36:16,193 --> 01:36:17,533
It didn't work out for you.

1763
01:36:17,569 --> 01:36:18,739
It happens sometimes.

1764
01:36:18,779 --> 01:36:20,239
Trudy's lawyer is not a patent attorney.

1765
01:36:20,280 --> 01:36:21,740
Which I said!

1766
01:36:21,782 --> 01:36:25,872
And you said I had no business
being Joy's advisor.

1767
01:36:25,911 --> 01:36:27,791
- And now it turns out that I was right!
- This is not helpful, Tony!

1768
01:36:27,829 --> 01:36:29,869
- That's enough, Tony. Please.
- It's enough, now?

1769
01:36:29,915 --> 01:36:32,675
I'm very sorry.
I wish there was more I could do.

1770
01:36:32,709 --> 01:36:35,919
But when your sister Peggy paid
the unjustified bills...

1771
01:36:35,963 --> 01:36:37,803
that you refused to pay...

1772
01:36:37,840 --> 01:36:39,420
it closed the door on that.

1773
01:36:39,466 --> 01:36:41,296
What about Neil Walker and QVC?

1774
01:36:41,343 --> 01:36:43,853
Wouldn't they pay the expenses
on defending the patent?

1775
01:36:44,596 --> 01:36:45,716
Be careful, Joy.

1776
01:36:45,764 --> 01:36:49,524
You could be sued for misrepresentation
and failure to deliver your product.

1777
01:36:49,560 --> 01:36:50,560
That's breach.

1778
01:36:51,520 --> 01:36:54,900
QVC requires that you deliver
a fully patented product.

1779
01:36:54,940 --> 01:36:57,440
I've been doing this for a long time.

1780
01:36:57,484 --> 01:37:01,574
You're in for a long court process
that will stall your product.

1781
01:37:01,613 --> 01:37:03,203
And you will probably lose.

1782
01:37:03,240 --> 01:37:04,660
I wish I could do more.

1783
01:37:06,285 --> 01:37:07,835
Take care, now.

1784
01:37:07,870 --> 01:37:10,210
You're gonna have to accept
the facts, Joy.

1785
01:37:10,247 --> 01:37:11,707
I mean, that's...

1786
01:37:12,332 --> 01:37:14,422
You're most of half a million dollars
in debt.

1787
01:37:14,459 --> 01:37:16,289
I don't know how you're gonna pay it.

1788
01:37:16,628 --> 01:37:18,418
We have to declare bankruptcy.

1789
01:37:18,463 --> 01:37:20,883
You're gonna have to declare bankruptcy.

1790
01:37:21,258 --> 01:37:22,548
I have to declare bankruptcy.

1791
01:37:22,593 --> 01:37:23,723
She has to.

1792
01:37:23,760 --> 01:37:25,300
- To try to contain my losses.
- Yeah.

1793
01:37:25,345 --> 01:37:26,635
I have to write it off.

1794
01:37:26,680 --> 01:37:28,720
It just seems so wrong.

1795
01:37:28,765 --> 01:37:30,425
We've worked so hard.

1796
01:37:30,475 --> 01:37:32,685
We've come so far
for us to just give up now.

1797
01:37:32,728 --> 01:37:34,308
It just seems so unfair!

1798
01:37:34,354 --> 01:37:36,984
Business is unfair. That's it.

1799
01:37:37,024 --> 01:37:39,154
It's not working out.
Well, that's what happens.

1800
01:37:39,193 --> 01:37:43,033
That's why people don't go around
making invention every other day.

1801
01:37:43,071 --> 01:37:44,161
Wake up!

1802
01:37:44,198 --> 01:37:45,318
It's my fault.

1803
01:37:45,365 --> 01:37:48,275
I gave her the confidence to think she was
more than just an unemployed housewife...

1804
01:37:48,327 --> 01:37:51,157
selling plastic kitchen stuff
to other unemployed housewives...

1805
01:37:51,205 --> 01:37:52,415
on a junk cable channel.

1806
01:37:52,456 --> 01:37:55,286
It's my fault.
It's not your fault, honey.

1807
01:37:55,334 --> 01:37:57,974
It was my mistake to make her think
that she was more than she was.

1808
01:37:58,378 --> 01:38:00,958
She pressured herself into doing
something she shouldn't have done.

1809
01:38:01,006 --> 01:38:03,166
It was wrong of you
to put that pressure on yourself.

1810
01:38:03,217 --> 01:38:05,547
It was wrong of us
to put that pressure on you.

1811
01:38:05,594 --> 01:38:07,184
I need more vodka.

1812
01:38:07,221 --> 01:38:12,981
It was wrong of us to think that you'd be
an instant business person overnight.

1813
01:38:13,018 --> 01:38:15,558
Of course, this is not who you are.

1814
01:38:16,522 --> 01:38:21,612
It takes a kind of toughness,
a certain acumen...

1815
01:38:21,652 --> 01:38:24,452
that you simply don't have.

1816
01:38:25,113 --> 01:38:26,453
Sign the paper.

1817
01:38:30,994 --> 01:38:33,584
You have to sign
these bankruptcy papers, honey.

1818
01:38:33,622 --> 01:38:36,172
The notary's right outside.
Let me get her.

1819
01:38:40,170 --> 01:38:42,370
You're gonna have to move
out of your house immediately.

1820
01:38:43,173 --> 01:38:44,893
You're gonna have to move
into an apartment.

1821
01:38:45,342 --> 01:38:47,552
Maybe you can move into a room
in Trudy's house.

1822
01:38:47,594 --> 01:38:48,854
With the children?

1823
01:38:48,887 --> 01:38:50,257
Yeah. You have room.

1824
01:38:51,181 --> 01:38:52,601
She's my daughter. Why not?

1825
01:38:53,934 --> 01:38:55,524
Let's talk about it.

1826
01:38:56,019 --> 01:38:57,649
Trudy, we have to offer her something.

1827
01:38:57,688 --> 01:38:58,808
Again?

1828
01:38:58,856 --> 01:39:00,066
Why me?

1829
01:39:07,865 --> 01:39:09,455
Please sign, honey.

1830
01:39:35,767 --> 01:39:36,887
Thank you.

1831
01:39:40,647 --> 01:39:45,067
Mimi said you were the one born
to help carry the family to success.

1832
01:39:48,572 --> 01:39:51,412
No, Cristy. Mimi was wrong.

1833
01:39:52,826 --> 01:39:55,196
The world does not give you opportunities.

1834
01:39:55,245 --> 01:39:59,995
The world destroys your opportunity
and it breaks your heart.

1835
01:40:00,626 --> 01:40:04,376
I should have listened to my mother
when I was 10 years old.

1836
01:40:04,421 --> 01:40:06,101
I should have spent the rest of my life...

1837
01:40:06,131 --> 01:40:09,181
watching TV and hiding from the world
like my mother.

1838
01:40:10,093 --> 01:40:12,683
So I don't wanna hear
any more about Mimi.

1839
01:40:13,263 --> 01:40:14,433
She was wrong.

1840
01:40:14,473 --> 01:40:18,063
She had her head in the clouds
and it was full of stupid ideas.

1841
01:40:18,101 --> 01:40:20,271
And it gave me stupid ideas.

1842
01:40:22,814 --> 01:40:23,824
Like this.

1843
01:40:26,652 --> 01:40:28,822
This stupid, stupid idea!

1844
01:40:31,782 --> 01:40:34,332
Mommy, don't tear them! No!

1845
01:40:56,056 --> 01:40:58,346
Cristy, I'm so sorry.

1846
01:40:58,392 --> 01:41:00,602
I'm sorry, Cristy.

1847
01:41:00,644 --> 01:41:02,314
I'm so sorry.

1848
01:41:02,354 --> 01:41:04,814
Please go to bed.
Everybody just go to bed.

1849
01:41:06,191 --> 01:41:07,941
Good night, Mommy.

1850
01:41:07,985 --> 01:41:10,155
Good night, sweetheart. Just go to bed.

1851
01:41:12,739 --> 01:41:15,239
I'm so sorry I failed you, Joy.
I'm so sorry.

1852
01:41:15,492 --> 01:41:17,082
Just, just don't.

1853
01:42:48,752 --> 01:42:50,962
Joy? Joy?

1854
01:42:51,630 --> 01:42:53,050
Joy, where are you?

1855
01:42:55,050 --> 01:42:56,800
Joy, where are you?

1856
01:44:10,501 --> 01:44:11,791
It's open.

1857
01:44:19,551 --> 01:44:20,891
You can leave the door open.

1858
01:44:46,870 --> 01:44:48,870
No one knows I'm here.

1859
01:44:49,873 --> 01:44:52,003
You don't even know who I am.

1860
01:44:52,042 --> 01:44:57,552
I could be Derek Markham or I might be
someone Derek Markham sent to handle you.

1861
01:44:58,048 --> 01:45:00,048
You have no case.

1862
01:45:00,551 --> 01:45:04,551
Maybe people think you came to Dallas
in despair to take your own life...

1863
01:45:04,596 --> 01:45:09,556
because you were in such deep financial
trouble suddenly from your little venture.

1864
01:45:16,233 --> 01:45:19,533
I made a phone call this morning
to Hong Kong.

1865
01:45:20,195 --> 01:45:25,365
It was 1:00 a.m. in California but it was 5:00 p.m.
the following afternoon in Hong Kong.

1866
01:45:25,409 --> 01:45:29,749
I always think it's amazing
how time works like that.

1867
01:45:31,456 --> 01:45:34,706
And I was fortunate enough to get
on the phone with Mr. Christopher...

1868
01:45:34,751 --> 01:45:37,921
who I found to be very friendly,
which was surprising...

1869
01:45:37,963 --> 01:45:41,223
because I really haven't found the
gentlemen in California to be very nice...

1870
01:45:41,258 --> 01:45:43,758
considering we're all
in business together.

1871
01:45:43,802 --> 01:45:47,602
Welcome to the world of business,
I guess.

1872
01:45:48,640 --> 01:45:51,060
I told Mr. Christopher
that the reason that I was calling...

1873
01:45:51,101 --> 01:45:55,111
was to discuss the differences
in the designs of our products.

1874
01:45:55,772 --> 01:46:00,242
But I quickly learned
that Mr. Christopher has no idea...

1875
01:46:00,277 --> 01:46:06,447
if his Hong Kong patent for a self-wringing
mop is worth anything or if it even works.

1876
01:46:07,075 --> 01:46:12,115
Because they have not made
or sold a single mop.

1877
01:46:12,414 --> 01:46:16,134
Unlike us, who have sold over 200,000.

1878
01:46:17,252 --> 01:46:22,132
And I've paid you over $50,000
in advanced royalties...

1879
01:46:22,174 --> 01:46:24,134
on behalf of Mr. Christopher.

1880
01:46:24,676 --> 01:46:29,596
Blood money from my family
and my second mortgage.

1881
01:46:30,849 --> 01:46:35,309
Turns out Mr. Christopher doesn't know
anything about those royalties.

1882
01:46:35,354 --> 01:46:36,814
So it seems...

1883
01:46:37,981 --> 01:46:41,611
we have a case of fraud and embezzlement.

1884
01:46:44,655 --> 01:46:47,825
And, as if that weren't bad enough...

1885
01:46:48,700 --> 01:46:54,330
I also discovered in the paperwork that
our mops actually don't bear any similarities.

1886
01:46:54,373 --> 01:46:57,503
So I never did owe you
any royalties for your patent.

1887
01:46:58,544 --> 01:47:00,504
That's another case of fraud.

1888
01:47:01,171 --> 01:47:07,181
My lawyers really could go after you,
but I told them, "Give me a day."

1889
01:47:07,219 --> 01:47:13,179
To see if maybe
you might've made a mistake...

1890
01:47:15,018 --> 01:47:17,978
that you would correct,
given the chance.

1891
01:47:33,370 --> 01:47:36,370
We'll pay you back all the royalties
you paid us.

1892
01:47:41,420 --> 01:47:46,050
I'll give you $20,000
on top of paying you back the 50.

1893
01:47:58,020 --> 01:47:59,230
Okay.

1894
01:48:00,939 --> 01:48:04,689
I'll give you $50,000
on top of paying you back the 50.

1895
01:48:16,747 --> 01:48:18,367
Plus interest.

1896
01:48:23,795 --> 01:48:25,795
I want all of my molds back.

1897
01:48:26,465 --> 01:48:28,765
I want you to sign
this piece of paper...

1898
01:48:29,801 --> 01:48:33,101
saying that you have
no rights, financially.

1899
01:48:34,097 --> 01:48:37,597
I'm just gonna add...
I said the 50...

1900
01:48:39,728 --> 01:48:41,648
plus the 50...

1901
01:48:43,440 --> 01:48:46,230
plus the interest.

1902
01:48:46,276 --> 01:48:50,406
So I just want you to initial
next to those two numbers as well.

1903
01:48:56,453 --> 01:48:57,953
So just sign there.

1904
01:49:05,963 --> 01:49:08,473
She put up with just about anything.

1905
01:49:09,466 --> 01:49:11,926
Until when she had to
bring the hammer down...

1906
01:49:13,470 --> 01:49:15,140
she brought the hammer down.

1907
01:49:17,474 --> 01:49:20,144
She couldn't know what was to come.

1908
01:49:21,019 --> 01:49:25,109
That she'd go on to make
another 100 record-setting patents.

1909
01:49:26,024 --> 01:49:29,744
Skinny velvet hangers
make neater closets.

1910
01:49:29,778 --> 01:49:32,108
That's a big deal to a lot of people.

1911
01:49:33,282 --> 01:49:35,702
I mean, who thinks of things like that?

1912
01:49:36,869 --> 01:49:38,159
Joy did.

1913
01:49:42,457 --> 01:49:47,667
She didn't know any of this would happen
as she walked down the street that day.

1914
01:49:48,338 --> 01:49:52,468
Yes, sir, tonight's the night for
Ol' Saint Nick to make his yearly visit...

1915
01:49:52,509 --> 01:49:54,639
to all the folks all over the world.

1916
01:49:54,678 --> 01:49:58,308
There's fun and expectation
in every house across the land.

1917
01:49:58,348 --> 01:50:02,438
And speaking of houses, what do you say
we take a little look-in on a typical one?

1918
01:50:05,439 --> 01:50:10,989
Now I'll admit that what you see right now
is just a small piece of the front of the house...

1919
01:50:11,028 --> 01:50:14,908
but all you grownups and kids alike,
this is the time for Santa's magic...

1920
01:50:14,948 --> 01:50:18,158
so I think we can make it
become a real house.

1921
01:50:19,036 --> 01:50:20,616
Even a house with love in it.

1922
01:50:20,662 --> 01:50:23,712
Mr. Santa Claus, can we have
a little snow, please?

1923
01:50:25,792 --> 01:50:27,712
Thank you. That's fine.

1924
01:50:28,003 --> 01:50:32,053
Now, Santa, let me see what it
really looks like inside this house.

1925
01:51:01,411 --> 01:51:05,921
She couldn't know that one day
she would move into a big beautiful home.

1926
01:51:08,502 --> 01:51:10,752
Her mother was happy.

1927
01:51:11,547 --> 01:51:15,877
She remained close to her,
and with the rest of her family...

1928
01:51:15,926 --> 01:51:18,676
which was, as always, complicated.

1929
01:51:20,848 --> 01:51:26,188
She would pay for products made by
Rudy, Trudy, and Peggy.

1930
01:51:26,228 --> 01:51:28,268
Even when they failed.

1931
01:51:28,939 --> 01:51:33,689
Even when they wrongly sued
for ownership of her company.

1932
01:51:34,570 --> 01:51:39,280
As Rudy got older,
Joy continued to take care of him and love him.

1933
01:51:45,122 --> 01:51:50,792
As Neil Walker predicted,
Joy did become a whole new business.

1934
01:51:51,253 --> 01:51:53,343
And even outgrew QVC.

1935
01:51:53,380 --> 01:51:55,340
- She's talking to her children.
- Is Tony in there?

1936
01:51:55,424 --> 01:51:56,724
Yes, Tony's in there.
The family's in there.

1937
01:51:56,967 --> 01:52:03,177
Her ex-husband and her best friend
would remain her steadfast advisers.

1938
01:52:03,223 --> 01:52:04,563
Please be patient.

1939
01:52:10,314 --> 01:52:12,614
I love you.
You guys go and pack your rooms.

1940
01:52:12,649 --> 01:52:14,439
- Good night, Mom.
- I love you.

1941
01:52:23,452 --> 01:52:24,702
- Hi.
- Hi.

1942
01:52:24,745 --> 01:52:26,415
- Welcome.
- Thank you.

1943
01:52:29,082 --> 01:52:30,292
What do you have?

1944
01:52:30,334 --> 01:52:32,134
A traveling clothes cleaner.

1945
01:52:32,169 --> 01:52:33,169
Let's see it.

1946
01:52:34,129 --> 01:52:35,419
So you're from Memphis?

1947
01:52:35,464 --> 01:52:36,804
Yes, I am.

1948
01:52:36,840 --> 01:52:38,130
You work as a waitress?

1949
01:52:38,175 --> 01:52:39,475
Yes, ma'am.

1950
01:52:39,510 --> 01:52:42,010
All right. Let's see it.

1951
01:52:43,514 --> 01:52:44,814
You made this yourself?

1952
01:52:44,848 --> 01:52:45,848
Yes, I did, ma'am.

1953
01:52:46,850 --> 01:52:49,100
I made my first invention myself, too.

1954
01:52:50,521 --> 01:52:52,521
I like this, it's a very good design.

1955
01:52:52,773 --> 01:52:53,773
